H. pylori prevalence in the three subgroups by sociodemographic characteristics is shown in Table I
. Among the 249 subjects, 81 (32.5%) tested positive for H. pylori. Logistic regression analysis showed that crude H. pylori prevalence was significantly higher in both groups A (OR=2.46; 95% CI 1.10–5.53; P=0.03) and B (OR=2.29; 95% CI 1.03–5.07; P=0.04) compared with group C (Table II
). These odds ratios do not change substantially when adjusted for sex, age and education level.
